[
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"413824\">@Gary Guo</span> I believe you told me about a challenge with the <code>const ptr</code> feature where it would required one of two different lowerings depending on whether the target is position-independent or not. However, I just ran into a similar issue with <code>sym</code> where this code:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"k\">use</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">std</span><span class=\"p\">::</span><span class=\"n\">arch</span><span class=\"p\">::</span><span class=\"n\">asm</span><span class=\"p\">;</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">static</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">MY_GLOBAL</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">i32</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">10</span><span class=\"p\">;</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">fn</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">main</span><span class=\"p\">()</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"kd\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">mut</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">addr</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"k\">const</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">i32</span><span class=\"p\">;</span>\n\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">unsafe</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"fm\">asm!</span><span class=\"p\">(</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"s\">\"lea {0}, [{1}]\"</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"n\">out</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">reg</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">addr</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"n\">sym</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">MY_GLOBAL</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"p\">);</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"p\">}</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"fm\">println!</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"s\">\"{:?}\"</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">addr</span><span class=\"p\">);</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>fails with</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>relocation <code>R_X86_64_32S</code> against <code>.rodata._ZN10playground9MY_GLOBAL17h21cfec9b2d52d43cE</code> can not be used when making a PIE object; recompile with -fPIE</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>And then it can be fixed by doing this instead:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"k\">use</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">std</span><span class=\"p\">::</span><span class=\"n\">arch</span><span class=\"p\">::</span><span class=\"n\">asm</span><span class=\"p\">;</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">static</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">MY_GLOBAL</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">i32</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">10</span><span class=\"p\">;</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">fn</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">main</span><span class=\"p\">()</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"kd\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">mut</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">addr</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"k\">const</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">i32</span><span class=\"p\">;</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">unsafe</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"fm\">asm!</span><span class=\"p\">(</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"s\">\"lea {1}(%rip), {0}\"</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"n\">out</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">reg</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">addr</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"n\">sym</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">MY_GLOBAL</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"n\">options</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">att_syntax</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"p\">);</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"p\">}</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"fm\">assert_eq!</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">addr</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">&amp;</span><span class=\"n\">MY_GLOBAL</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">as</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"k\">const</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">i32</span><span class=\"p\">);</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Is this the same issue? Perhaps the fact that it is a problem for <code>sym</code> too could mean something interesting for the <code>const ptr</code> case too? Thoughts?</p>",
        "id": 532020293,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1753953006
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>No, this is expected, this passes the compiler and assembler and is the linker telling you that you're doing it wrong</p>",
        "id": 532021133,
        "sender_full_name": "Gary Guo",
        "timestamp": 1753953240
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You'll have the same issue by just referring to symbol name. For i operand it'll be rejected by LLVM directly at compiler level of target is PIC</p>",
        "id": 532021427,
        "sender_full_name": "Gary Guo",
        "timestamp": 1753953316
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So could you remind me the issue? The problem is that you want to use <code>i</code>, but in cases where LLVM rejects it, you want to emit the symbol name instead?</p>",
        "id": 532021909,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1753953458
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Symbol name + offset</p>",
        "id": 532022034,
        "sender_full_name": "Gary Guo",
        "timestamp": 1753953491
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But there is no way to do it directly, so I would always need to some templating and at least the offset needs to be emitted directly</p>",
        "id": 532022165,
        "sender_full_name": "Gary Guo",
        "timestamp": 1753953531
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What do you mean by no way to do it directly?</p>",
        "id": 532022274,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1753953564
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>No way to juse use a constraint and give it the pointer value, like I constraint</p>",
        "id": 532022683,
        "sender_full_name": "Gary Guo",
        "timestamp": 1753953678
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ok</p>",
        "id": 532023119,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1753953790
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"413824\">@Gary Guo</span> What about the <code>m</code> operand? Is there a reason you can't use that instead of <code>i</code>?</p>",
        "id": 532039905,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1753958705
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Sorry for all the questions, but I thought I would throw together an RFC for the const ptr feature.</p>",
        "id": 532040411,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1753958858
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I guess with <code>i</code> you can get the address directly in a <code>mov</code> instruction, whereas with <code>m</code> you'd need a <code>lea</code> instruction to do that.</p>",
        "id": 532042736,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1753959599
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>m</code> generates  <code>[sym + offset]</code> so you cannot use actually as an address</p>",
        "id": 532042915,
        "sender_full_name": "Gary Guo",
        "timestamp": 1753959648
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Which we would need for static keys</p>",
        "id": 532043088,
        "sender_full_name": "Gary Guo",
        "timestamp": 1753959699
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Does this mean that we actually need two different operands? One for people who want the address, and another for people who want the location.</p>",
        "id": 532043099,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1753959701
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes. Also most people who want <code>m</code> also want something of runtime address, not just a constant one</p>",
        "id": 532043241,
        "sender_full_name": "Gary Guo",
        "timestamp": 1753959742
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Does one of the other operands already support that case?</p>",
        "id": 532043317,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1753959770
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Or is this just also missing?</p>",
        "id": 532043331,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1753959775
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's just missing.</p>",
        "id": 532043351,
        "sender_full_name": "Gary Guo",
        "timestamp": 1753959782
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>:/</p>",
        "id": 532043385,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1753959792
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Currently you have to put it in a register and use <code>[{}]</code></p>",
        "id": 532043402,
        "sender_full_name": "Gary Guo",
        "timestamp": 1753959796
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Imagine for a moment that we added a <code>memory</code> operand as an equivalent to the <code>m</code> case. What kind of RHS would it accept? I guess you can also use a local variable there?</p>",
        "id": 532043615,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1753959855
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But it still has to be \"compile-time\" logic ...</p>",
        "id": 532043710,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1753959884
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So ... is it const eval where you are allowed to get pointers with the address of local variables?</p>",
        "id": 532044026,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1753959997
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Sorry I am not getting it</p>",
        "id": 532044698,
        "sender_full_name": "Gary Guo",
        "timestamp": 1753960254
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The <code>m</code> can generate things like <code>[rsp + 0x30]</code> or <code>[rip + ...]</code> or move address to a spare register and generate <code>[reg]</code></p>",
        "id": 532044792,
        "sender_full_name": "Gary Guo",
        "timestamp": 1753960282
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That's the output, not the input.</p>",
        "id": 532044847,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1753960303
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Like, in my C code, I'm gonna write <code>m (something)</code></p>",
        "id": 532044886,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1753960318
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm just trying to imagine what it would look like if Rust asm did support it.</p>",
        "id": 532045040,
        "sender_full_name": "Alice Ryhl",
        "timestamp": 1753960378
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ah</p>",
        "id": 532045558,
        "sender_full_name": "Gary Guo",
        "timestamp": 1753960556
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Probably just a pointer or reference?</p>",
        "id": 532045589,
        "sender_full_name": "Gary Guo",
        "timestamp": 1753960567
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It looks like the m operand (unlike i operand) only supports lvalues, so it seems a Rust version of that could just use any place expression like the <code>in(_)</code> operand does.</p>",
